agicon|SCO}} Freed\n| 30 Apr 1948\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Reserve team==\nDumbarton entered the Scottish Second XI Cup but lost in the first round to Ayr United.\n\n==Trivia==\n* The number of goals conceded in all games during the season was 111, the 12th time the unwanted 'century' had been broken.\n\n==See also==\n* [[1947\u201348 in Scottish football]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://sonsarchive.com/player.php?id=5853 Finlayson (Dumbarton Football Club Historical Archive)]\n*[http://sonsarchive.com/player.php?id=377 Jim Hoey (Dumbarton Football Club Historical Archive)]\n*[http://sonsarchive.com/player.php?id=601 Alex Kay (Dumbarton Football Club Historical Archive)]\n*[http://sonsarchive.com/player.php?id=5852 Jimmy Michie (Dumbarton Football Club Historical Archive)]\n*[http://sonsarchive.com/player.php?id=522 Ian Hepburn (Dumbarton Football Club Historical Archive)]\n*[http://sonsarchive.com/player.php?id=597 John Kelly (Dumbarton Football Club Historical Archive)]\n*[http://sonsarchive.com/player.php?id=614 Gordon McFarlane (Dumbarton Football Club Historical Archive)]\n*[http://sonsarchive.com/player.php?id=5854 Bobby Caldwell (Dumbarton Football Club Historical Archive)]\n*[http://sonsarchive.com/player.php?id=590 Hugh Docherty (Dumbarton Football Club Historical Archive)]\n*[http://sonsarchive.com/player.php?id=606 Peter Grant (Dumbarton Football Club Historical Archive)]\n*[http://sonsarchive.com/player.php?id=595 Eddie McCreadie (Dumbarton Football Club Historical Archive)]\n*[http://sonsarchive.com/player.php?id=603 Neil McLean (Dumbarton Football Club Historical Archive)]\n*[http://sonsarchive.com/player.php?id=604 John McLennan (Dumbarton Football Club Historical Archive)]\n*[http://sonsarchive.com/player.php?id=584 Dave Morrison (Dumbarton Football Club Historical Archive)]\n*[http://sonsarchive.com/player.php?id=594 Jimmy Shields (Dumbarton Football Club Historical Archive)]\n*[http://sonsarchive.com/player.php?id=598 Edwin Wagstaffe (Dumbarton Football Club Historical Archive)]\n*[http://sonsarchive.com/player.php?id=599 John Wardlaw (Dumbarton Football Club Historical Archive)]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20141129035238/http://www.scottish-football-historical-archive.com/ Scottish Football Historical Archive]\n\n{{Dumbarton F.C. seasons}}\n{{1947\u201348 in Scottish football}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dumbarton}}\n[[Category:Dumbarton F.C. seasons]]\n[[Category:Scottish football clubs 1947\u201348 season]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2015}}\n{{Infobox football club season\n| club               = [[Dumbarton F.C.|Dumbarton]]\n| season             = 1947\u20131948\n| manager            = William Guthrie\n| chairman           = \n| stadium            = Boghead Park, Dumbarton\n| league             = [[1947\u201348 Scottish Football League|Scottish League B Division]]\n| league result      = 11th\n| cup1               = [[1947\u201348 Scottish Cup|Scottish Cup]]\n| cup1 result        = Third Round\n| cup2               = [[1947\u201348 Scottish League Cup|Scottish League Cup]]\n| cup2 result        = Prelims\n| cup3               = [[B Division Supplementary Cup]]\n| cup3 result        = Second Round\n| league topscorer   = John Wardlaw (13)\n| season topscorer   = Jackie Cantwell (16)\n| highest attendance = \n| lowest attendance  = \n| average attendance = \n| prevseason         = [[1946\u201347 Dumbarton F.C. season|1946\u201347]]\n| nextseason         = [[1948\u201349 Dumbarton F.C. season|1948\u201349]]\n}}\n\nThe '''1947\u201348''' season was the 64th [[Football in Scotland|Scottish football]] season in which [[Dumbarton F.C.|Dumbarton]] competed at national level, entering the [[Scottish Football League]], the [[Scottish Cup]], the [[Scottish League Cup]] and the [[B Division Supplementary Cup|Supplementary Cup]].  In addition Dumbarton competed in the [[Stirlingshire Cup]].\n\n==Scottish Football League==\n{{Main|1947-48 Scottish Football League}}\nA poor start, which saw only one point taken from the first 5 league games, meant that any hopes of challenging for promotion were quickly dashed and eventually Dumbarton finished 11th out of 16 with 25 points - 28 behind champions East Fife.\n\n{{football box collapsible\n|result  =L\n|date =13 August 1947\n|round =[[1947-48 Scottish Football League|Division B]]\n|score = 2\u20131\n|team1 =[[Raith Rovers F.C.|Raith Rovers]]\n|team2 =[[Dumbarton F.C.|Dumbarton]]\n|goals1 = {{goal|}} {{goal|}}\n|goals2 =Cantwell {{goal|}}\n|stadium =[[Starks Park]]\n|attendance =\n|referee =\n|motm =\n}}\n{{football box collapsible\n|result  =D\n|date =27 August 1947\n|round =[[1947-48 Scottish Football League|Division B]]\n|score = 2\u20132\n|team1 =[[Dumbarton F.C.|Dumbarton]]\n|team2 =[[Stenhousemuir F.C.|Stenhousemuir]]\n|goals1 =Morrison {{goal|}}<br>Donegan {{goal|}}\n|goals2 =McFarlane {{goal|}}{{goal||72}}\n|stadium =[[Boghead Park]]\n|attendance =\n|referee =W Webb\n|motm =\n}}\n{{football box collapsible\n|result  =L\n|date =20 September 1947\n|round =[[1947-48 Scottish Football League|Division B]]\n|score = 4\u20132\n|team1 =[[Leith Athletic F.C.|Leith Athletic]]\n|team2 =[[Dumbarton F.C.|Dumbarton]]\n|goals1 =Landells {{goal|11}}<Br>Broadly {{goal|28}}<Br>Roberts {{goal|53}}<br>Skinner {{goal|70}}\n|goals2 =Shields {{goal|17}}<br>Bootland {{goal|65}}\n|stadium =[[New Meadowbank]]\n|attendance =3,500\n|referee =J McDonald\n|motm =\n}}\n{{football box collapsible\n|result  =L\n|date =27 September 1947\n|round =[[1947-48 Scottish Football League|Division B]]\n|score = 2\u20134\n|team1 =[[Dumbarton F.C.|Dumbarton]]\n|team2 =[[St Johnstone F.C.|St Johnstone]]\n|goals1 =Goldie {{goal|11||74}}\n|goals2 =Brown {{goal|26||64}}<br>Goldie {{goal|35}}<br>Mayes {{goal|72}}\n|stadium =[[Boghead Park]]\n|attendance =2,000\n|referee =[[Jack Mowat]]\n|motm =\n}}\n{{football box collapsible\n|result  =L\n|date =4 October 1947\n|round =[[1947-48 Scottish Footba